          "body": "The psalm closes with the Psalter's most concentrated statement of divine faithfulness in a single verse. Three movements: a declaration, a ground, and a petition. The declaration — 'The Lord will accomplish what concerns me' — uses *gamar*, to complete or finish, with the preposition *bead* (on behalf of, concerning). What God has begun in the believer He will bring to completion; the divine initiative does not stall midway. The ground — 'Your lovingkindness, O Lord, is everlasting' — provides the covenant foundation for the declaration: God will accomplish because *chesed* has no time limit. Then, remarkably, the psalm ends not with confident declaration but with humble petition: 'Do not forsake the works of Your hands.' This is not a contradiction of the confidence — it is its highest form. The believer who most truly believes God will accomplish his deliverance is the one most compelled to petition for it. Maaseh *yadekha* — the works of Your hands — applies the language of craftsmanship to the believer's life: God has made something; David appeals to that creative investment. As the psalm began with a whole heart given to thanks, it ends with a whole heart given in appeal — both grounded in the same everlasting *chesed*."
