        "excerpt": "All the kings of the earth will give thanks to You, O Lord, when they have heard the words of Your mouth.",
        "body": "The psalm's perspective expands dramatically from David's individual heart to the entire political landscape of the world. The escalation is deliberate: the same *yadah* (give thanks) that David offered in verse 1 will be offered by all the kings of the earth. The scope is universal — every human authority without exception. And the catalyst is *hearing*: 'when they have heard the words of Your mouth.' Not conquest, not political persuasion, not cultural pressure — the spoken word of God is what draws the nations to praise.\n\nVerse 5 specifies the content of their praise: 'the ways of the Lord.' *Derekh* (way, path) in the Psalter refers to God's characteristic patterns of action — how He typically moves in history on behalf of the helpless, against the proud, in faithfulness to His covenant. The kings will sing of those ways because 'great is the glory of the Lord.' *Kavod* (glory) — literally, weight, substance, the reality that makes something worth attending to. The nations will not be coerced into doxology; they will be compelled by the undeniable weight of divine glory revealed in divine action.\n\nVerse 6 provides the theological warrant (*for*) for why this worldwide praise is not mere optimism. The God who will receive universal worship is the God who is simultaneously exalted (*rum*, on high) and attentive to the lowly (*shaphal*). The proud He knows 'from afar' — *rachaq*, at a distance. This is not merely a sociological observation about humility being rewarded; it is a statement about the nature of divine attention. Proximity to God is the inverse of self-elevation. Jonathan Edwards, in his *Discourse on the Nature of True Virtue*, captures the dynamic: the creature who bows most is most seen by the One who is highest.\n\nThe canonical resonance of these verses is extensive. Isaiah 45:22-23 (all the ends of the earth will be saved and bow); Philippians 2:10-11 (every knee will bow, every tongue confess); Revelation 15:3-4 (the nations will come and worship before You). David's psalm is not merely personal aspiration; it is prototypically messianic — the worldwide worship it anticipates will find its fulfillment in the universal lordship of Christ.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kavod* (glory, v.5) — literally *weight*; the substance that makes something impressive and undeniable. *Derekh* (ways, v.5) — God's characteristic patterns of action in history. *Rachaq* (from afar, v.6) — distance as a theological statement about God's relationship to pride."
