        "excerpt": "Though I walk in the midst of trouble, You will revive me; You will stretch forth Your hand against the wrath of my enemies, and Your right hand will save me.",
        "body": "Verse 7 is the psalm's pastoral climax — the point at which cosmic theology descends into present, personal need. David is not using past-tense language here; he is 'walking' (*halakh*, present continuous) in the midst (*qerev*, the center, the thick) of trouble (*batstsarah*, distress, tightness, no room to maneuver). The cosmic vision of verses 4-6 has not resolved his personal crisis. The God of universal glory is the God he needs right now, in the middle of current threat.\n\nThe three divine actions of verse 7 are precise. First: 'You will revive me' (*chayah* — to keep alive, to preserve vitality). This is not the dramatic rescue language of battle but the quieter preservation of someone who might otherwise expire under the weight of prolonged trouble. God maintains the life-force of His servant in the middle of the crisis. Second: 'You will stretch forth Your hand against the wrath of my enemies' — *shalach yad* is the language of divine intervention against hostile force. The enemy's *aph* (wrath, literally 'nostril' — the seat of anger in Hebrew idiom) is countered by a divine hand. Third: 'Your right hand will save me' (*yamin*... *yasha*). The right hand (*yamin*) in Old Testament military imagery is the sword hand, the hand of power and victory (Exodus 15:6; Psalm 18:35). God does not merely observe David's trouble; He acts on both fronts — against the threat and toward the threatened.\n\nTheologically, this verse teaches that God's preservation is co-extensive with the trouble, not subsequent to it. He does not wait for the crisis to end before reviving; He revives *within* the crisis. Douglas Moo's principle from James 1:3-4 — that the test produces endurance before it produces relief — finds its Old Testament counterpart here: God does not exempt from trouble but sustains through it.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chayah* (revive, v.7) — to live, to sustain life, to bring to life; the same root as *chai* (life). *Yamin* (right hand) — the hand of strength and victory in OT warfare; contrasted with the left hand of ordinary action. *Batstsarah* (trouble) — tightness, constriction, from a root meaning narrow straits."
